<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-268-655  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 268 655.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Jan 9 1989 n520 p45(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Still no. 1: maintaining the U.S. high-tech lead. (includesrelated article about author Daniel Queyssac) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Queyssac, Daniel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US is still the leading innovator in semiconductor technologyin the world, despite stories to the contrary.andP;  The Japanese haveexcelled and surpassed the US in some areas, such as memories, butthey have yet to break the innovation lead established by the US.andO;The US displays this lead in the new field of RISC processors,which are currently being developed by several companies.andP;  OtherUS innovations in development include the digital signalprocessor, modems for fax machines, non-volatile memories,programmable array logic devices, and ASICs.andP;  The US also staysahead in software, as evidenced by the universality of MS-DOS andUnix.andP;  The US will stay on top with innovations in investment, aswell.andP;  Some of the old rules for investments are outmoded.andP;  Acompany should allow at least five years to judge if it has made agood investment in the semiconductor industry.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Semiconductor IndustryCreativityUnited StatesHigh TechnologyResearch and DevelopmentCompetitionForeign Competition.andO;Feature:   illustrationcartoon.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>